The soft_fuzzy.py file contains the python code that incorporates the fuzzy logic while categorizing each sequence into low length, medium length and large length sequences while mining.
The soft_fuzzy.fasta file is the input file that contains leprosy sequences.
The r_softFuzzy_low contains the low length sequence results that were mined when the .fasta file was run against .py file.
The r_softFuzzy_medium contains the medium length sequence results that were mined when the .fasta file was run against .py file.
The r_softFuzzy_high contains the high length sequence results that were mined when the .fasta file was run against .py file.

************************************

## **Complete Comparison Table**

| Feature | CRISP | FUZZY | SOFT | SOFT-FUZZY |
|---------|-------|-------|------|------------|
| **Data Type** | Raw counts | Proportions | Raw counts | Proportions |
| **Grouping** | All together | All together | 3 length groups | 3 length groups |
| **Normalization** | None | By sequence length | None | By sequence length |
| **Support Divisor** | Total amino acids | # sequences | Total AA per group | # sequences per group |
| **DataFrames** | 1 (bio_df) | 2 (bio_df, fuzzy_df) | 4 (bio_df + 3 groups) | 7 (bio_df + 3 groups + 3 fuzzy) |
| **Functions** | Single set | Single set | Triple set | Triple set |
| **Output Files** | 1 | 1 | 3 | 3 |
| **Complexity** | ‚≠ê | ‚≠ê‚≠ê | ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê | ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê |
| **Computation** | Fastest | Fast | Moderate | Slowest |

**************************************

## Characteristics: of SOFT FUZZY

Normalized proportions (membership values)
Three length-based groups
Divides by number of sequences in each group
Best of both worlds: Length-aware + normalized

*****************************************

## **Practical Decision Tree**
```
Are your sequences similar length (< 20% variation)?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Use CRISP (fast, simple, sufficient)
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Continue...

Do you need to compare patterns across length ranges?
‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Continue...
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ Do you have computational resources?
‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ YES ‚Üí Use SOFT-FUZZY ‚≠ê (best accuracy)
‚îÇ       ‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Use SOFT (good compromise)
‚îÇ
‚îî‚îÄ NO ‚Üí Use FUZZY (good normalization, simpler)


*********************************************

## **Which One is BEST?**

### **ü•á Best Overall: SOFT-FUZZY (Code 4)**

**When to Use:**
- ‚úÖ Sequences vary significantly in length (e.g., 50-500 amino acids)
- ‚úÖ You want the most accurate, unbiased analysis
- ‚úÖ Need to discover length-specific compositional patterns
- ‚úÖ Research/publication quality results
- ‚úÖ You have computational resources and time

**Why Best:**
1. **Eliminates length bias completely** - normalizes within each sequence
2. **Discovers length-dependent patterns** - separate analysis per group
3. **Most accurate representation** - proportion-based within length groups
4. **Fair comparison** - each sequence contributes equally within its group
5. **Comprehensive insights** - can compare patterns across length ranges

**Example Use Case:**
```
Protein dataset: Signal peptides (20-40 aa), domains (100-200 aa), 
full proteins (300-800 aa)

SOFT-FUZZY will:
- Normalize composition within each sequence
- Group similar-length sequences
- Find patterns specific to short, medium, long proteins
- Avoid long proteins dominating the analysis
```

---

### **ü•à Second Best: FUZZY (Code 2)**

**When to Use:**
- ‚úÖ Sequences have variable lengths but you want overall patterns
- ‚úÖ Simpler analysis needed
- ‚úÖ Don't need length-specific insights
- ‚úÖ Faster results required

**Why Good:**
- Normalizes for length differences
- Simpler than Soft-Fuzzy
- Good balance of accuracy and speed

---

### **ü•â Third Best: SOFT (Code 3)**

**When to Use:**
- ‚úÖ Need length-based grouping
- ‚úÖ Raw counts are meaningful (e.g., absolute abundance matters)
- ‚úÖ Simpler than Soft-Fuzzy

**Why Moderate:**
- Groups by length (good)
- But doesn't normalize within sequences (less ideal)
- Long sequences in each group still have more influence

---

### **‚ùå Least Recommended: CRISP (Code 1)**

**When to Use:**
- ‚úÖ All sequences are similar length (¬±10%)
- ‚úÖ Quick exploratory analysis
- ‚úÖ Teaching/learning purposes
- ‚úÖ Computational constraints

**Why Limited:**
- No length normalization
- No grouping
- Biased toward longer sequences
- Only use if sequences are uniform length
